<paragraph blockId="9.[92,1047,211,491]" pageId="9" pageNumber="2014">
This subfamily is distributed from Africa to New 
<collectingCountry box="[724,808,211,235]" name="Guinea-Bissau" pageId="9" pageNumber="2014">Guinea</collectingCountry>
(table 4). There are four species in Africa, one in 
<collectingCountry box="[443,503,243,267]" name="India" pageId="9" pageNumber="2014">India</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[566,644,244,267]" name="Myanmar" pageId="9" pageNumber="2014">Burma</collectingCountry>
and eleven in the East Indies and Australasia. The widespread occurrence of this family in Africa and 
<collectingCountry box="[908,1047,275,299]" name="Madagascar" pageId="9" pageNumber="2014">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
suggests that its primary evolutionary centre was Africa and that the family had reached 
<collectingCountry box="[192,252,339,363]" name="India" pageId="9" pageNumber="2014">India</collectingCountry>
before that subcontinent became united with southern Asia, from whence this family spread into the East Indies and Australasia. The presence of six species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Agassiz" authorityYear="1846" box="[217,310,403,427]" class="Insecta" family="Apachyidae" genus="Apachys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dermaptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="2014" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[217,310,403,427]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="2014">Apachys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<collectingCountry box="[358,463,403,427]" name="Australia" pageId="9" pageNumber="2014">Australia</collectingCountry>
may either represents a migration across with a united Gondwanaland or one from New 
<collectingCountry box="[574,657,435,459]" name="Guinea-Bissau" pageId="9" pageNumber="2014">Guinea</collectingCountry>
, during a period of low sea level Jackson, (1995).
</paragraph>
